<sn><md>### Silicate Minerals

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
Silicate minerals are the **largest and most abundant group** of minerals on Earth. They are built around the **silicon–oxygen tetrahedron (SiO₄)**, a four-sided structure that forms the basic building block of all silicates.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![diagram](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Orthosilicate-2D-dimensions.png/250px-Orthosilicate-2D-dimensions.png)
:::
:::

#### General Characteristics of Silicate Minerals
* Contain **silicon (Si)** and **oxygen (O)**.
* Structure based on **SiO₄ tetrahedra**, which may exist as single units or linked in chains, sheets, or 3D frameworks.
* Usually **light-colored** and less dense.
* Highly resistant to weathering depending on the structure.
* Form the bulk of Earth’s **crust and mantle**.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Major Silicate Groups

![diagram](https://static.cambridge.org/binary/version/id/urn:cambridge.org:id:binary:20170919094839570-0492:9781316661888:fig2_1.png?pub-status=live)

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Nesosilicates{.text-center}
Independent Tetrahedra<br>
Tetrahedra do not link; remain isolated.<br>
Examples: **Olivine, Garnet**
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Sorosilicates{.text-center}
Double Tetrahedra<br>
Two tetrahedra share one oxygen atom.<br>
Example: **Epidote**
:::


:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Cyclosilicates
Ring Silicates<br>
Tetrahedra link into rings of 3, 4, or 6 units.<br>
Examples: **Beryl, Tourmaline**
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Inosilicates{.text-center}
Chain Silicates<br>
* **Single-chain**: Pyroxene group
* **Double-chain**: Amphibole group
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Phyllosilicates
Sheet Silicates<br>
Tetrahedra form sheets with perfect basal cleavage.<br>
Examples: **Mica, Talc, Chlorite, Clay minerals**
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Tectosilicates
Framework Silicates<br>
Three-dimensional structures; most abundant silicates.<br>
Examples: **Quartz, Feldspar, Zeolite**
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Non-Silicate Minerals

Non-silicate minerals `do not contain SiO₄ tetrahedra`. They make up a smaller but diverse group with important economic and industrial applications.

#### General Characteristics of Non-Silicates

* Absence of silicon–oxygen tetrahedra.
* Usually **denser** and may show metallic luster.
* Many are economically valuable **ores of metals**.
* Form in sedimentary, metamorphic, and hydrothermal environments.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Major Non-Silicate Groups

| Group               | Key Composition | Description                       | Examples                       |
| ------------------- | --------------- | --------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| **Carbonates**      | CO₃²⁻           | Minerals containing carbonate ion | Calcite, Dolomite              |
| **Oxides**          | O²⁻ + Metals    | Oxygen bonded with metallic ions  | Hematite, Magnetite            |
| **Sulfates**        | SO₄²⁻           | Minerals containing sulfate ion   | Gypsum, Anhydrite              |
| **Sulfides**        | S²⁻ + Metals    | Sulfur bonded with metals         | Pyrite, Galena, Chalcopyrite   |
| **Halides**         | Cl⁻, F⁻, Br⁻    | Minerals containing halogen ions  | Halite, Fluorite               |
| **Phosphates**      | PO₄³⁻           | Minerals containing phosphate ion | Apatite                        |
| **Native Elements** | Single Element  | Pure elemental minerals           | Gold, Silver, Copper, Graphite |
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Key Differences Between Silicate and Non-Silicate Minerals

| Feature          | Silicate Minerals          | Non-Silicate Minerals            |
| ---------------- | -------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Main Composition | SiO₄ tetrahedra            | No SiO₄ tetrahedra               |
| Abundance        | ~90% of Earth’s crust      | ~10% of Earth’s crust            |
| Structure        | Chains, sheets, frameworks | Simple ionic/covalent structures |
| Color            | Often light                | Often dark/metallic              |
| Economic Value   | Common rock-formers        | Major metal ores                 |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Summary

Silicate minerals dominate Earth’s crust due to the abundance of silicon and oxygen, forming complex structures. Non-silicate minerals, though less abundant, include many important industrial and metallic ore minerals. Both play crucial roles in geology, Earth processes, and human industry.
</md></sn>